{"key":"post-10050362","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10050362</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; Unlike the mirro's with a weight, this doesn't exhaust the steam until you reach 26psi.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Don't forget to leave the toggle open for the first few minutes after steam begins to escape.&amp;nbsp; You need to get all the air out.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You can use a sterilizer to can, but you have to watch it like a hawk and open the toggle valve &lt;i&gt;exactly&lt;/i&gt; as it cools to zero psi.&amp;nbsp; If you fail to do that, it pulls a vacuum in the sterilizer itself, and the jar lids don't seal tight, thus you don't get a vacuum inside the jars where you need it.&amp;nbsp; In addition, it causes the liquid in the jars to boil over.&amp;nbsp; I use my AA 921 for canning food and sterilizing agar.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The main problem with the 941 is it's so damn heavy on your stove burner, and with many of the smaller, cheap-ass made in mexico and china ranges today, it's impossible to position it where the burner is in the center of the PC.&amp;nbsp; The 25X and 75X plug into a wall outlet, so you don't have that problem.&amp;nbsp; The sterilizers also have a thermostat, so you can set them and go watch a movie without constantly being there to adjust your stove burner through the cycle.&amp;nbsp; I run my 75X at 20 psi.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10050629</next>\n<prev>10050284</prev>\n<first>10046671</first>\n<last>22140061</last>\n<when>1238132501</when>\n<utime>03/27/09 08:41 AM</utime>\n</post>"}